Scientists have found a way to find related stars
Astrophysicists from the University of California at Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow you to look among the stars related, that is, arose from one cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and briefly they can be found on the website of the university.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearest stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, which precedes the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the stellar cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the stars-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulations carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, scientists using a supercomputer simulated two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
This object, within a few million years under the influence of its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added label paints to the original gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieved a high degree of chemical uniformity.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to look for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
