Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that would protect trade unions as a civil right.
“Where unions are, there are middle-class jobs,” says Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chairs the Progressive faction Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to present the Workers’ Empowerment Act along with the Civil Rights Movement symbol, John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal opportunities to discriminate against trade union organisations as other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of opponents of trade unions.
Amending the Labour Regulations Act in such a way as to allow workers facing discrimination for participating in trade union organizations to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive damages and penalties - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill offer is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have been subjected to in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country – Americans once supported countries around the world in adopting, expanding and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo's militarized autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions played a role in the formation of a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve the working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and to every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will not have legal effect; measures aimed at these purposes will be considered unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration of Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to defend their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted as a proper basic provision that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions — and to have that union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — should be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as well.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights – and the extension of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against trade union organisations – are long overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis revive the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge temporarily blocked a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of the Louisiana law, which his supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under the measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginadl in June and was due to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients in hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can now continue to perform legal abortions, continuing to seek such powers.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing their powers of attorney,” Judge John deGravells wrote in his ruling.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month, during which the judge will render a more permanent decision on this law.
Advocates of the right to abortion welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authority.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a treacherous law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit to suspend the law on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to the doctors from the two clinics who had not acted as plaintiffs in the case and had also applied for admissions.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts have recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would have closed most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admissions laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, the doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission authority await a decision.
What will lead to the introduction of quotas for domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of goods in the range of trade networks should be Russian-made, according to the Deputy of the State Duma from the faction "Fair Russia" Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, writes the newspaper "Izvestia".
The document will be further detailed in order to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. <0x3C>...> For the rest of the groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers,” Nilov told the publication.
Together with the amendments to the article "On the basis of state regulation of trade activities in the Russian Federation", the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, which establish a reduced VAT rate of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in trade networks is included in the package of incentive measures for Russian manufacturers.
On the shelves will appear several times more domestic goods.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company “Nalogovik”, a member of the independent expert center “Public Duma” Sergey Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
In addition, there will be farmers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate to retailers their terms and prices, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will lead to higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will start to expand, some will learn faster, will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, however, not immediately," the expert said.
Previously, Russian enterprises were often unable to break into the shelves of local stores due to the high competition from foreign analogues.
Now, after the embargo, this niche has been released and you can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary checks, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will arrive on the Russian market.
In other words, now there is a "moment of calm", when the former players have already left, and the new ones have not yet come.
Almost a month later, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in prices for finished products," said the first Vice-President of the All-Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors", Ph.D. Tamara Kasyanova.
Definitely, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will secure the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, rather than with goods that, at the expense of subsidies from another state, are cheaper.
In other words, the fight for the buyer will unfold between companies operating under the uniform laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanov notes, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots far from all the articles.
And in this situation, the trade networks will have to “reach” the share of Russian goods to half of the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that the shelves will receive low-quality goods.
Perhaps under the guise of being produced in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied,” the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in such a scenario, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, as the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not exclude that the law on quotas for domestic goods can affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter as a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, was again talked about by economists in February this year due to the ongoing devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers in the formation of orders to suppliers to consider domestic producers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the path of import substitution, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," said Deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example, in the dairy sector, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to fully cover the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, meat production can get a powerful boost.
As you know, the largest share of imports is preserved on beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% is still accounted for by Russian products," Kasyanov said.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and may accelerate this process.
However, this initiative will not lead to import substitution in itself, since it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that full import substitution will not take place, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
In addition, it is not enough to establish quotas, it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees and will provide", - the expert states.
Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women in rural Australia face a higher risk of death from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
The researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after the diagnosis was made.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research reported that those living in regions and remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
LARGE RESEARCH: New Drugs May Slow Down Lung Cancer and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers followed the medical path of women for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said the age of the woman at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not intended to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that an untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly in large cities," she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of on-the-go services that would allow professionals to treat women closer to home and support programs for people undergoing treatment away from home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Neve, was told that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
