The inflation peak of 9% will be in February, after which the annual rate of price growth will go down, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after the Russian Federation imposed "clean sanctions".
AiF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, Head of the Analytical Department of FC AForex:
Prices are already rising in the main product segments.
Moreover, when socially important products began to be valued, the government was forced to launch measures to systematically monitor price stability in order to prevent the risks of unwarranted price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting to regulators on a daily basis so that authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiates price increases.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the colossal pace of capital outflows, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian megaregulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, as well as an embargo on the import of food products from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressure remained under control, the cost of a basket of the minimum set of products would not jump by 12% in just a quarter.
The ban on the import of food products caused a supply shock in the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final value.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the import substitution mechanism, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to bear the risks of growth of the inflation component.
If we add to this the fiscal reasons associated with the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the worsening prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvaev, Director of the Analytical Department of Alpari
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in zero it was also above the current level, another thing that was then compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think that at the end of the year inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Plato Maguta, asset manager of the Maguta Foundation
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is still being successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, first of all, on the financial sector - this can lead to certain difficulties and increase inflationary expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in purchases of cash currency in order to secure their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But the rise in prices traditionally begins after the summer calm and, perhaps, this autumn will become more tangible.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to stand, as Russia has more financial savings.
