China's largest companies join forces against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China’s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (China’s largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the wonder of the Chinese Internet, which has left even its American rivals – eBay and Amazon.com – behind, will not be easy.
The Union of Largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% - each of the Internet companies, Wanda Group said in a statement.
It is planned to register the company in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu’s search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda’s infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial real estate properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and theme park in Qingdao (a city in eastern China on the shores of the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American network of cinemas AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest cinema operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by the newly created competitor Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will head the new company, thanks to the merger Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is set to become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, according to Dong Tse.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O are coupon sales services such as Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the largest cake in online commerce,” Wanda Wang Jianlin, the CEO, told Bloomberg.
“There is no real O2O site in China right now, and in this situation everyone has roughly equal chances,” he said.
China’s e-commerce market is the world’s largest, and McKinsey & Co. estimates its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011 to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has risen to 632 million, according to official statistics by Bloomberg, which is more than the population of any country in the world except India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015, this number can grow to 850 million people.
The Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was the richest man in China until recently, however, according to the Bloomberg Millionaires Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu leader Robin Li is now the third richest person in China, while Wang Jianlin of Wanda is the fourth.
“It’s very interesting to watch this battle: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the even richer,” said Bloomberg, director of China’s e-commerce research center in Hangzhou, Cao Lei.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to compete seriously with Alibaba immediately after the creation: "Rome can not be built in one day."
The fact that with Alibaba is not so easy to compete not only with new companies, but also well-deserved leaders of the world Internet trade, evidenced published on the eve of the report on the financial performance of Alibaba for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as something between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June, the Chinese company earned more than both of its U.S. competitors combined.
Alibaba’s net profit over the period is almost twice that of its competitors – it has almost tripled year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has a huge potential for generating money, thanks in large part to its mobile apps,” said a report by analyst Arete Research Service in Hong Kong.
According to the updated Alibaba prospectus on the website of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company’s services in July amounted to 188 million, significantly exceeding the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions over the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba has to name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba’s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) could take place as early as September 16.
The road-show of the company, which precedes this event, will start on September 3.
Alibaba’s exit to the IPO is expected to be a record in NYSE’s history and will allow the company to raise about $20 billion.
So far, the record for the amount of funds raised on U.S. exchanges belonged to the payment system Visa, which in 2008 held the initial placement of its shares, earning $ 17.9 billion.
