Calculation of estimates of construction facilities in the Russian Federation will occur in a new way
Issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks, the Federal Antimonopoly Service takes special control.
Under the FAS, an expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector was established.
At his meeting, the head of the Department of control of housing, construction and natural resources of the FAS Vadim Solovyov said that "today's calculation of the estimates of construction facilities is absolutely incomprehensible."
The normative base makes pricing opaque and can lead to unreasonable construction costs, according to the FAS.
And they propose the cost of construction of state-owned facilities at the design stage to determine on the basis of market prices of constructive solutions instead of the estimated norms and unit prices for technological operations used today.
These proposals are included in the “road map” and are now under consideration in the Ministry of Construction.
“The replacement of traditional estimated documentation in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry,” Vadim Solovyov explained.
After all, now every bolt and nut is calculated in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes in the documentation unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors".
The Ministry of Finance agrees with the FAS.
"The first developments on the transition to the calculation of cost on constructive elements already exist: methods for calculating prices for constructive solutions, drawing up estimates on these indicators have been developed," said Elena Zhukova, Head of the Department of Urban Planning and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction.
The field of road construction was chosen as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko told RGB, the estimated standards have long been outdated, but no other mechanism has yet been proposed to the business.
"As for the proposed calculations for structural elements, in practice it is difficult to implement, because in the construction of buildings often use completely different technologies," he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely due to the state order.
According to the Chairman of the Board of NP "Expert community of professionals of state order" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, Deputy Director of Engineering of Rosatom’s industrial capital construction center, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts, and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is maximally protected from someone’s managerial influence.
At the expert council, it was proposed to form a system of state procurement in such a way that the same executor is not entitled to receive more than one contract in the amount of more than 1 billion rubles or several contracts in the amount of more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case it will be necessary to assign the customer the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the regular number of the customer and budget costs for its maintenance.
At the same time, the specialists of the customer will have to have knowledge that allows to assess the quality of the work performed by the contractor organizations, as well as their safety.
Often, with such a breakdown, it will be necessary to determine who will be responsible for the safety of the object as a whole.
In addition, this approach may lead to the outflow of highly qualified public procurement participants due to the lack of interest in obtaining a state order for incomplete work and a small contract amount.
Oleksandr Evstashenkov, Deputy Head of the Expert Advisory Center of the Procurement Institute, believes that now the state procurement procedure has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And gave an example: "the participant when filling out the application must specify "specific indicators" without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "should be", "from", "more", "less", "analogue", "or", "type", "similar type", "not lower", "below", "above", "may", "may have", "may not", "before".
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of an application submitted by contractors.
Another problem 44-FZ, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to evaluate the quality of work through the "paper" offer of the participant at the stage of application.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to evaluate only the qualification of the contractor, but not the quality of work, which has not even begun to perform, - the expert believes.
The quality of work can be assessed only when it is accepted.
At the expert council, it was also proposed to move the marginal income from the upper to the lower echelon so that intermediate contractors would disappear.
Chairman of the Expert Council, State Secretary, Deputy Head of the FAS Andrey Tsarikovskiy believes that this should not be done, since the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
And otherwise it will turn out, as in the famous rerun of Arkady Raikin "Atelier": "To the buttons there is a claim?".
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and mines rained on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory recovered from fighting.
The start of schooling brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of hostilities remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the Pashosh kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed the traces of fragments from the walls and children's slides before the arrival of students.
“We’re a little scared, but we’re looking forward to the future,” said Ronit Barth, a resident of Kibutza Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Barth, said it was “a bit strange” to start school again.
“It was a difficult time and we didn’t leave our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is located near the border with Gaza, to express his support.
Before a cease-fire deal halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not go outside or left their homes, leaving for safer areas farther from Gaza to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mine, doubt that they should go back.
The Ministry of Education said that about a dozen families have not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools for the time being.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu attended a school in Sderot, a city on the border with Gaza that has become heavily damaged by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, “We will do our best to give you knowledge and ensure your safety.”
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce on Tuesday.
The cease-fire immediately put an end to hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of whom were civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel contests these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other militants in Gaza fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
As a result of Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip have been damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 250,000 people have found refuge in more than 100 schools, which have been converted into shelters.
Because tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and fighting continued, officials in charge of education postponed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza’s schools.
According to the popular criterion, real estate prices showed the highest winter growth in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic housing price index for the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
This increase led to a cumulative increase of 4.2 per cent in June, July and August, the largest increase in the winter months since 2007.
Annual price growth was 10.9 percent, more than double the 12-month growth as of August 2013, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
RP Data Research Director Tim Lawless said Sydney and Melbourne are leading a two-tier market.
RP Data figures show that housing prices in Sydney rose 16.1 percent over the past year, while in Melbourne they rose 11.7 percent.
The next most powerful markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose on average from five percent to six percent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which was followed by government spending cuts, where prices rose by only 1.4 percent per year.
Mr Lawless said that now that spring has begun, there will be an increase in the number of properties put up for sale over the next few months, which will be a “real test” for the market.
“Given the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sales, and the current low-interest conditions, it is likely that the cost of housing will rise further over the next three months,” he said.
How people live in the oldest house of Ufa
In the former house of gold-industrialists and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 (formerly Bolshaya Kazanskaya) 18 apartments.
The house of the XVIII century since the time of construction has hardly changed, except for the old age.
Foreigners come here as a tour, and the tenants suffer more than they rejoice from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians indicate two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is not nearly 300 years old.
The old courtyard, always an open door, a creaking staircase.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls cracked, and in the lumens of the peeled plaster in places the street is visible.
I think it's all about honesty.
And the locals say, "You don't think so."
Living in a wooden house of the XVIII century is very difficult, - says Tatyana Lukyanov, resident of apartment No 3.
The object is on the state depository, but money for its maintenance is not allocated for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits that the authorities simply forgot about.
The last repair was 40 years ago.
The walls are still lean-poor, but the foundation is all rotten.
Many residents still go to the toilet outside and wash once a week in a public bath.
How can you be happy in such conditions?
The road passes right under the windows, there is not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls back the curtain.
Now you can see what was only heard before: under the windows the flow of cars.
You see, the windows are constantly shivering, we can not open the windows, and we are used to the noise.
People get used to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to her husband, his hands are golden.
I have two bedrooms and I live with my son.
And other families have much worse conditions, on the second floor in general ceilings a little more than one and a half meters high.
To contrast, Tatiana offers to visit a neighbor from apartment No. 6 Lyudmila Starostina.
A pleasant hospitable woman from the threshold offers a cup of coffee and with a sad smile says:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m2 for four people, so we live: my husband and daughter with a granddaughter.
I have been here since birth, there has never been another living space, - Lyudmila looks around the room: mezzanines, two sofas with the letter "G"; on one of them there is a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very narrow and little different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historic".
But from the ceiling regularly flows: the plumbing system is not suitable anywhere.
Lyudmila talks about her apartment everyday and surprisingly at the same time, as an Italian woman, whose house stands on the Roman ruins.
That is, it boils down to one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The plumbing was carried out about 40 years ago during the last repair.
Then they made us a small kitchen in a corner and a toilet from a former closet.
We live right where Demidov lived with his family, on the second floor there lived servants.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The Ufa Real Estate Center says that privatization does not matter.
We will still get only a one-room apartment, we can not claim more.
Four months ago, they promised to resettle us, but it did not go beyond the promises.
I'm not used to complaining, and I won't.
In this apartment (room!) lived a whole dynasty: my grandmother and grandfather, mom and dad, my husband and my daughter and granddaughter.
Everything has happened during this time.
For example, large rats ran in the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the wing, they are meter-thick!
They say the solution was mixed on eggs, which is why it lasts so long.
The house was built thoroughly, thank you Demidov!
Probably only because no one has been killed by the collapsed ceiling or his own.
Only the building is still slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house rot, the floors repeatedly collapsed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground, as in a well.
They say that it is - under our room a secret ravine and the passage to the river Bela, which was specially made by the old believers who once lived here, so that it was possible to hide from danger, in case of what.
They were persecuted.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begging them to let him start excavating in the apartment.
And then he persuaded them to give them the living space in exchange for his odnushka on October Avenue.
Lyudmila refused the historian:
Where are the four of us?
And here, at least a tiny hope that will give housing more spacious.
If we agreed to the exchange, we wouldn't have won anything.
However, the old family did not win anything.
Lyudmila's biggest dream was to be resettled, and her daughter with a 16-year-old granddaughter was given a separate room.
That is, two families have allocated a two-room apartment instead of the most majestic ruins, in which two generations live now.
Cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments No. 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two narrow rooms with a total area of 23 m2, called apartments, her large family lives.
There are seven of us, two children.
You can see what the conditions are.
The plaster falls off in pieces, like window frames, in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms through holes.
The water in the tap is only cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house of Ufa, you can make sure that the spouses of Lavrentyev from apartment No. 4 were the most lucky.
They occupy the most spacious rooms on the first floor.
You're right, there's plenty of room!
The room is 75 square meters, three people are registered.
We live in the rooms where Suvorov, according to legend, stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high and spacious.
One bad thing - everything around cracks at the seams, falls apart, collapses.
Neighbors have already told me!
The most torment we have with the floors: the wooden boards rotted, the earth literally slipped from under our feet.
I put up supports, wedges; there is nothing in the hall yet, and in the other room we walk, as we swing on the rocks, everything is so fragile.
About the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov Alexander Dmitrievich can tell better than any guide.
The gold-industrialist treats him as a native, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of Kaginsky and Uzyansky factories built houses, cast guns and bells, held Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestor, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the XX century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then around stood wooden rooms for carriages, stables and guard booths, subsequently demolished.
In 1968, we wanted to clean our house, but something prevented us from doing it.
History repeated itself in 2014: again lured to new housing.
We, as a team, collected all the documents, bypassed the necessary authorities, and suddenly learned that the move to apartments is postponed to 2015 or 2016.
We don't believe in all this anymore...
Two years ago, Lavrentyev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to learn about the fate of the house.
Residential officials did not accept it.
They were sent from one table to another, and then, as a mockery, they issued a paper without signature and seal: "The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of tenants."
I even have the feeling that our house is not in the plan of the city for a long time, because first it was under the number 57, then it became 57 A, and now it is 57/1.
It's like it was taken down in the '70s.
"Russian Planet" appealed to the head of the information and analytical work of the management of land resources of Ufa Vladimir Barabash.
The house on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 is included in the program of resettlement of old housing.
I cannot be held responsible for the actions of officials in the 1970s, but I do know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite the historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities - to restore all the old houses on the street of the October Revolution, representing architectural value - is successfully implemented.
Residents will soon be resettled in new apartments.
According to Barabash, the restoration of the House of Demidov will be Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
Now in Italy there is an architectural biennale, and the project "Old Ufa" is presented there among others.
I hope that by 2016, the entire former Old Kazan street will be restored, - says the official.
The houses will have a proper look, corresponding to the one that was before, three centuries ago.
Demidov’s house will most likely become a museum open to everyone.
In addition, at the government level, it was decided to make the street on weekends pedestrian.
On weekdays, unfortunately, it will not work, too much traffic in the city.
Vladimir Barabash promises to resettle people from the future museum in 2015.
However, it is unlikely that they will be satisfied: their new apartments will be the same area as the current ones.
Only from another era.
In Primorye due to a thunderstorm began a forest fire
Dry thunderstorm caused a forest fire on the territory of the Hunting sectional forest in the Pozhar district of the Primorsky Territory.
At the site of the fire, the grouping of forces and means is being built up.
According to the management of the KGSBU "Primorskaya Air Base", the conditions created at the site of the fire require the involvement of aviation forces.
Vasily Medvedev, Deputy Chief of Air Base:
The fire, which occurred in hard-to-reach terrain, was detected by an observer pilot aboard an An-2 patrol aircraft on an area of 3 hectares.
Burning wood residue on an old burner.
The strong congestion of the territory and the steepness of the slope of more than 45 degrees, the absence of paratrooper-fire sites suitable for landing create significant difficulties in extinguishing.
We need a Mi-8 helicopter.
The delivery of forces at the disposal of the air base by Mi-2 helicopter and An-2 aircraft is very difficult.
After detecting the fire at the place of extinguishing were quickly landed 4 parachute firefighters.
