Production growth in the eurozone slowed to its lowest level in 13 months in August, according to a popular study.
The latest Markit business activity index (PMI) of the euro area manufacturing sector fell to 50.7 in August, falling from 51.8 in July.
A value above 50 indicates an increase.
New orders have been delayed and businesses have suffered amid growing tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The figures came ahead of a meeting of the European Central Bank (ECB) on Thursday.
Markets will expect a clear plan from the bank on how to deal with a halt to the recovery of the eurozone, as well as the threat of deflation at inflation, which is only 0.3%.
There is a suggestion that ECB chief Mario Draghi may give additional signals later this week that he is considering a quantitative easing scheme for the eurozone similar to those used by the UK and the US during the financial crisis.
“Although some growth is better than no growth at all, the inhibitory effect of growing economic and geopolitical uncertainty on producers is becoming more apparent,” said Rob Dobson, Markit’s senior economist.
The PMI of Germany’s manufacturing sector, Russia’s largest trading partner in the EU, fell to its lowest level in 11 months, at 51.4.
Meanwhile, in the bloc’s second-largest economy, France, PMI fell to 46.9.
France continues to cause real concern, as does Italy’s weakening from steady growth to stagnation.
Signs that the momentum of growth has faded in the main industrial engine, Germany, as well as in Spain and the Netherlands, also do not add confidence," Dobson said.
The slowdown in the industry is likely to fuel analysts waiting for additional monetary or fiscal stimulus.
One positive news came from Ireland, where PMI rose to 57.3, its highest level since late 1999.
Howard Archer, chief economist at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing to say about the August survey of the business activity index of the euro area manufacturing sector is that it shows that the sector is still growing.”
He added: “The eurozone’s producers obviously find life very difficult at the moment, as the current increased geopolitical tensions – especially with Russia/Ukraine – add uncertainty to the still-difficult conditions in many countries.
This heightened tension has obviously hit the business – and especially consumer confidence – and is likely to lead to some orders being delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
