4 tips on how to achieve better quality underwater photos and videos
If you want to take photos or shoot videos underwater, there are a number of equipment options in front of you.
The cheapest option is a waterproof “soap” such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or an action camera such as the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which sell for about $300.
I took these pictures at a family holiday with a few cameras, all for about $350.
No matter what equipment you use, a few rules need to be followed in order to achieve the best results.
Check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the camera battery and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also, set up your camera for the type of photos or videos you’re going to shoot.
Some camera and video cameras have shooting modes or object types that optimize exposure for darkened underwater conditions.
And before jumping into the water, figure out how deep your equipment can sink.
Some cameras are designed for only 5 feet, others - 50 or 60 feet.
Check out our customer guide and digital camera ratings for both traditional and waterproof models.
Take a few shots - because many of them will not work.
The "soaphouses" have LCDs that will help you compose photos, while the action cameras usually do not.
Even if you have an LCD, it will be difficult to see underwater, and the layout of the frame will be a random process.
So make a few shots.
Also, if your camera has a serial shooting mode that shoots multiple frames with slightly different exposure settings, use it.
Stay at the surface.
The amount of light is significantly reduced the deeper you dive underwater.
If possible, stay at the surface when you shoot in a pool, river, or ocean.
It will also allow you to convey more color in photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Swim closer to the subject.
This is great advice for shooting on land, but it is even more important under water due to darkened light conditions.
