The Ministry of economic development wants to accelerate the growth of the electric car market
This week, the Ministry of Economic Development will submit to the government a comprehensive plan for the development of environmentally friendly transport in Russia, said Deputy Director of the Department of the Ministry Oleg Pluzhnikov at a round table held by Vedomosti at the Moscow Motor Show in 2014.
The plan was drafted on behalf of the government, one of the main goals is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
The document is expected to be adopted in late September - early October, Pluzhnikov says, the proposed measures concern electric vehicles and hybrids - a plan for the development of vehicles on gas-powered fuel in Russia already exists.
The plan (a copy is available at Vedomosti) is designed for 2014-2017.
It is necessary to develop criteria for the assessment of electric and hybrid transport and to decide how to stimulate the use and production of environmentally friendly vehicles.
The report to the government, which will describe tax and customs measures to support electric vehicles, will be prepared by December 2014; the preferential lending and preferential leasing scheme will appear by April 2015; and proposals to reduce the price of cars, stimulate localization and create service infrastructure will be developed by October 2015.
In 2014-2015, it is planned to amend the regulations to facilitate the conditions for the construction of charging infrastructure (in parking lots, gas stations, etc.).
In addition, federal officials intend to formulate proposals for regional authorities in 2015 to also encourage the use of environmentally friendly transport - in the form of providing it with an advantage in driving and parking, for example; and by February 2016 - and proposals to expand public procurement of such transport.
Finally, by October 2014, the Ministry of Economic Development will include criteria in the list of indicators for assessing the activities of regional authorities, reflecting the effectiveness of supporting the production of environmentally friendly transport and the development of charging infrastructure.
The market of electric cars in Russia is still being formed - in 2013 about 100 electric cars were sold throughout the country.
At the beginning of 2014, the import duty on electric cars was nullified, so sales will be about 500 pieces, predicts the CEO of Mitsubishi Motors in Russia Andrei Pankov.
But the five-fold increase does not make electric cars any noticeable: in 2013, in Russia, according to the Association of European Business, 2.78 million cars and light commercial vehicles were sold.
So far, only Mitsubishi Motors imports electric vehicles to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start importing - the company focuses primarily on corporate customers, says Renault's Director of Strategic Planning and Partnerships in Russia Nicolas Remiz.
Most of the other electric vehicle manufacturers have taken a wait-and-see position on Russia.
The development of electric vehicles is also at the Russian manufacturers - "", GAZ, "" but the output is miserable.
For example, in January-July 2014, according to ASM-holding, AvtoVAZ produced 30 electric vehicles.
Demand is low due to the high cost of electric vehicles, admits the director of "AvtoVAZ" for engineering Sergey Amanov, without state support there will be no breakthrough in this segment.
The development of the Russian market of electric vehicles in addition to the high cost of cars (the electric cars sold in Russia, on average, twice as expensive as analogues with internal combustion engines) restrains the underdevelopment of charging infrastructure (refueling stations - units), says CEO of "Autostat" Sergey Tselikov.
Due to the high cost and low rates of reducing the cost of electric cars in the next 3-4 years will remain a niche segment of the Russian market, predicts the editor-in-chief of "Avtorev" Mikhail Potozhansky, Tselikov agrees with him.
Automakers, on the contrary, say that some models of electric cars are already close to the cost of conventional ones.
The Russian electric car market has good prospects, the main thing is to instill confidence in consumers that “electric mobility” is real; this, in particular, will contribute to the emergence of more and more new charging stations, emphasizes the President of the BMW Group in Russia Wolfgang Schlimme.
Such infrastructure projects are being implemented, for example, by the state-owned company Rosseti: several stations have been built in Moscow, and about 80 more will soon appear.
Negotiations on the construction of a network of gas stations are underway with other regions.
According to Vladimir Sofiin, director of the Rosseti department, the company believes in the electric car market and is ready to build gas stations throughout the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric cars in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric cars of various brands.
In addition, "Rosseti" as a network company does not have the right to sell electricity, the possibility of doing so in relation to charging electric vehicles is being worked out.
Pankov believes that the most effective measure of state support for the formation of the market of electric vehicles in Russia is the nullification of customs duties.
The zero rate will be valid until the end of 2014, the possibility of its extension, expansion of the preferential list is being worked out.
Replacing the transport tax with an environmental tax (the idea is discussed and applies to all machines) will also support the market, but not as tangible as customs preferences, Pankov said.
Transport tax in Russia is small, says Pankov, unlike, for example, Norway, where the tax reduction has led to a sharp increase in sales of electric cars - now they account for 12% of the market.
In Russia, incentives for car owners are also needed, for example, free parking in the city center (as they have already done in Moscow), Pankov is sure, or the possibility of moving electric cars along dedicated lanes, which Russia does not yet have.
