A genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed.
The British woman said she had spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karin Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she only had a few years left to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (SMT), a group of hereditary disorders that lead to nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have CMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure gait, and clenched toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, which means that the symptoms intensify over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrich Ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be chained to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and would die before she was 30.
The mother of two, who is now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what the others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I was never able to ride roller skates or skateboards with other kids, and I was bullied a lot in school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at the medical card when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I put my nose where I shouldn’t, and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that interval.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease because you'd be in a wheelchair by now."
I think you have something that poses a much smaller threat to life.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have CMT.
“When he explained what CMT was, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The charity SMT UK announced a month of information about the SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The tax burden on entrepreneurs of the Washington zone is growing as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and more jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose moderately last year, when economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington zone are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to the state treasury and locally in fiscal 2013, 3.8 percent more than the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on state and local businesses rose 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after years of contraction in 2009 and 2010.
Taxes levied by the state rose faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county's tax revenues, 56 percent, are from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenues are from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the smallest amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, the increase in tax revenues is driven by a return to the previous level of the company’s real estate value, the researchers say, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row, when growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large share of this revenue comes from large states such as California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same thing is happening in the Washington zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 — a 4.2 percent increase from the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate has no similar effect on rising state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of corporate tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of the state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their property, especially the tax base around District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a nonprofit organization that doesn’t pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more on, for example, income taxes to pay for the same services as there are in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs’ incomes also seem to be improving, according to these data.
Companies in the region have declared a $2.3 billion corporate income tax at the state level, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although trends are directed in the same direction, the tax burden on entrepreneurs at the local level does not increase at the same rate in all three localities.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average of 4.3 per cent, while the growth rate in Maryland was significantly faster, at 4.9 per cent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each having the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 per cent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 per cent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is experiencing competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs even up to 3% by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington zone seem to feel better and thus pay more taxes by state and local level, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneurial taxes paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners – the transitional structure that has arranged most small businesses – in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher growth rate than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington zone may lag behind, as the reduction in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
