Ways to Save Money on University Textbooks
Although the cost of university textbooks for many students exceeds $1,000 a year, Matt Schroeder, who will soon move to the second year, came up with a clever way to reduce costs.
He developed a system of how to rent books from high school students, offering them nominal compensation so that they postponed their sale.
“My textbook on mathematical analysis, which usually costs $180, I got for a semester for $10 and a Chick-fil-A cookie,” says Schroeder, 19, who is studying at Covenant College in Georgia.
The required literature for the last semester would have cost $430, he says.
He spent $120.
According to the Council of Colleges, the average student spends more than $1,200 a year on textbooks and school supplies, but students have a number of options to reduce these costs.
Students are increasingly choosing online stores and creative ideas similar to Schröder’s system.
Book rental is becoming increasingly popular, allowing students to use the book for a semester, and is often significantly cheaper than buying them.
Nibo Incorporated, which owns more than 250 university bookstores, reports that the volume of book rentals has doubled since 2011.
Industry research shows that about a quarter of the books in university bookstores during the last spring semester were rented, says Nibo Vice President Trevor Meyer.
Less than half of all books are purchased in university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Stores.
Here is an introductory course on the best ways to make a profitable deal.
Shopping in the online store
Sometimes, if you go online, the price of a new book can be one-third of what you see in a university bookstore.
The ninth edition of "Mathematical Analysis" by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler costs about $290 per ticket, but a new copy can be purchased for $239.99 at Chegg.com, which specializes in selling textbooks.
Buying a used
If you don’t mind other people’s marks or damage, used textbooks are a good option.
"Mathematical Analysis" is sold for $93.49 in second-hand form on Chegg.com.
Matt Caseday, a 25-year-old fourth-year student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a second-hand copy of “Strategic Decisions in Media: Understanding the Business Side of the Advertising Business.”
The book sold for $48.
Teachers, for example, Ingrid Bracey, director of the College without Walls at the University of Massachusetts at Emherst, invites students to check with their professors whether they should use previous editions.
Sometimes updates are insignificant for classes.
In such cases, old editions can often be found at a very small fraction of the cost of the last edition.
In addition to Chegg and Amazon, Half.com, owned by eBay Inc., is a popular alternative to buying used books.
Lease
It is worth thinking about how to rent textbooks, if you treat them well enough, do not forget to return them and do not want to keep them to yourself after the course is completed.
You can save more than 80% on the cost of a new book.
For example, one student was able to rent "Mathematical Analysis" for a semester for about $20.
Find out the rules of the store where you take the books, including any fines you may be issued for marks, underscores, and damages.
If you rent a book, remember: if you do not return the book, the fines may even exceed the cost of a new copy.
E-books
E-books instead of traditional textbooks are another option.
Sometimes such books are actually rented, acquiring an electronic license for a certain period from distributors, for example, Amazon.com, Chegg and Barnes & Noble Inc.
The rental of "Mathematical Analysis" on the site Chegg.com for six months will cost about $ 61.
Bracey says that students studying literature can often find the most favorable prices, as many classic works can now be downloaded for free, while literature in the natural and engineering sciences can be quite expensive.
No matter what, take a look around.
Joe Golt, 29, who is about to start studying at Pepperdine Law School, recommends using the ISBN number to find out the price of the book, as this ensures that you are looking for exactly the text you need.
Before ordering online, says Golt, be sure to check if the book is really in stock.
This lesson was not easy for him.
The delivery of the book he purchased was delayed for four weeks, and he eventually paid the full price at the university bookstore.
