"Europrotocol" instead of traffic police
Casco payments can be received without a traffic police certificate - so the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of the "Euro-protocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft of guidelines, according to which from September 1 this year to receive payments under the casco insured motorist will be able to do without a traffic police certificate.
This is true only in cases where the accident was registered under the “Europrotocol” without the participation of the road police.
That is, if only two cars were involved in the accident, there are no physically injured persons, the damage does not exceed the established limit, and both drivers have reached an agreement on who is responsible for the accident.
From August 2, the limit of payments under the "Europrotocol" is 50 thousand rubles, and from October 1, in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in the Moscow and Leningrad regions, it will be increased to 400 thousand rubles.
The bottom line is that often, even with minor damage, in a situation where an accident can be registered under the "Europrotocol", drivers who have been in an accident cause DPS.
After all, in the presence of a policy kasco to get a refund on it without a certificate of traffic police was not possible.
The parameters spelled out in the draft guidelines are precisely designed to eliminate this obstacle to the introduction of the "Euro-protocol" in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payment under the casco in connection with an accident, executed without traffic police officers, should not be lower than the limit under the "Europrotocol".
But at the same time, it can not be higher than the limit set in the insurance contract of the casco.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically able to unload both DPS employees and roads.
But, most likely, it will not be pleased either motorists or insurers.
The latter are already talking about a serious threat of the growth of fraud, which can lead to the introduction of new rules for payments on the casco.
As for drivers, it is difficult to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome the primordial Russian conservatism.
In most cases, the driver will wait for hours for the inspector to arrange a minor accident, because it is more reliable.
And it is still unknown what will be easier - to defeat fraudsters or convince drivers of the reliability of the "Euro-protocol".
Savings certificate will be made nameless and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates on the bearer, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of the irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban savings certificates on the bearer.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that savings certificates for the bearer do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since there is no need to make a deduction to the fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken due to small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and it will affect Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to ASV estimates, control 98% of the profile market.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the ASV, is that customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his license, are trying to get money from the ASV.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates on the bearer, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments under these certificates in case of withdrawal of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tensions.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court," the ASV said.
The problem, of course, is contrived.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, because they do not have the right to reimbursement from the state by law.
If it were that the instrument was not insured in the ADR, it would also prohibit metal accounts on which citizens' funds are counted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, however, their existence is not yet threatened by anyone.
The fact is, most likely, that bearer certificates are a very convenient security, which can actually act as a quasi-dene.
At the same time, their movement is almost uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer to any citizen, and before cashing out such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the draft law stipulates that a savings certificate must necessarily be a name security, which must be kept in the depository.
And to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of the irrevocable contribution, which bankers have long dreamed of, is introduced.
