A potential way to steal nude celebrity photos has been discovered
The massive hacking of star accounts may have been caused by a vulnerability in the Find My Phone app.
The potential scenario of events described the resource The Next Web.
Github published a script in the language of Python, which allowed you to select passwords for the service Find My Phone Apple.
This service allows you to track the location of the iPhone.
To access it, the same combination of login and password of Apple ID is used, as for access to the Apple iCloud cloud, from which photos of celebrities were stolen.
The script allowed the search method to recognize the password from Find My Phone.
In this method, all sorts of combinations of characters are consecutively entered, starting with the most commonly used passwords.
The author of the script claimed that the number of password options entered in the Find My Phone service is unlimited.
If the security system is properly organized, after several unsuccessful attempts to enter the wrong password, the account should be blocked and inform the user of the attempted hacking.
Due to the vulnerability, users did not receive any messages about an attempt to retrieve a password to their account.
Hackers learned the password from Apple ID and used it to access iCloud.
According to a hackapp user on Twitter, the vulnerability was discovered two days ago, on Saturday, and a password-selecting scripting program was written to it.
At the moment, the vulnerability is closed: after five attempts, access to the service is blocked.
The resource contacted Hackapp and noted that the above vulnerability is typical for many services, but noted that there is no evidence that such a vulnerability was used to access the account "stars".
