The Investigative Committee of Russia (ICR) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and flight engineer.
The forensics showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of landing, the failure of the crew to perform standard procedures on landing, as well as the unintentional output of engines to increased direct thrust speeds.
The Tu-204 aircraft of Red Wings, which followed the flight from Prague to Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 while landing at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft rolled out of the runway and caught fire.
At the scene of the accident, the commander of the aircraft, the second pilot and flight engineer were killed.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical facilities, where they subsequently died of their injuries.
Three other flight attendants, hospitalized with severe bodily injuries, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, which was moving at the time of the accident on the Kiev highway, suffered serious injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
After the crash, the traffic prosecutor’s office conducted an inspection at Red Wings, during which numerous violations were detected.
In February 2013, the license of the airline was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
