Anger is the most universal and functional human emotion.
An angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists in Australia and the United States found.
They reported their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release of the University of California at Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face is shifted and lowered eyebrows, stretched in a thin line of lips, bloated nostrils - the same in all cultures, and make it even blind from birth children who have never seen it, says the lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion arose for the effective conduct of disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can cause to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he reports it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers also found confirmation of another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and go on hand-to-hand, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and prefer forceful methods of resolving conflicts to peaceful ones.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining", the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry facial expression should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force as soon as possible to agree to his conditions in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated on a computer faces where each of the seven elements of the angry face were present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or a forwarded chin separately did not make the face evil, the physically stronger person was recognized by the study participants unanimously.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own strength, forcing one to accept and obey.
A person inflates his nostrils and squeezes his lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that shows off its fangs.
“Anger is triggered by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes a form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite side the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tuby.
The Ministry of communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV and radio company "Crimea"
In 2014, the Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "TV and Radio Company "Crimea".
This is stated in the draft decree of the government, prepared by the department, which was read by "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed “to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment”.
In particular, for the allocated money, it is planned to re-equip the hardware and studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The State Broadcasting Company "Crimea" was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the TV and radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Crimea TV and Radio Company" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
